They say, that they block no application, however in epp_logs.zip we can see that they are using a policy called "HOD POLICY - TEST", and this policy blocks both Skype and WhatsApp with the following rules:

Skype.exe
Skype.exe --skype
WhatsApp.exe
WhatsApp.exe *

On Escalation Ticket # 00421750 the new comment has been added: Robert-Zoltan Sumi:

@WaitingOnEngineer

Hi Andrei, I checked the logs. They show, that there were cases when epp-client received 2 policies, 1 and even 0. When epp-client has not blocked Whatsapp epp-client had no policies. I can not tell why, it could happen that

	 - 	all policies were turned off on the server
	 - 	the server has not sent any policies despite there were active ones
	 - 	epp-client has not read the policy from reprovision.db (this would be strange because other settings were read)

Please check again, and collect the logs, reprovision.db and options.ini the monent when the issue reproduces. I need to know what reprovision.db contained at that moment. The last reprovision.db was probably saved after Whatsapp blocking worked again, because it contains a policy, which was read by epp-client.

On Escalation Ticket # 00421750 the new comment has been added: Robert-Zoltan Sumi:

@WaitingOnEngineer

Hi Andrei, I checked the logs.

There is no policy loaded until 10:16:59. Before this, Whatsapp was started at 04:09:09, which seems to be normal, because there were no policies loaded.

At 10:13:00 "NORMAL USER POLICY" was loaded.

Between 10:13:55 and 10:14:07 there were 7 attempts to start Whatsapp, but according to the logs these were all blocked.

What was the time when the customer reproduced the issue?

@WaitingOnEngineerHi, blocking Whatsapp website should work if they remove "
*.whatsapp.com" from the domain whitelist (Denylists and Allowlists -> Allowlists -> Deep Packet Inspection).

Previously they said that their only problem remained that Whatsapp Web is not blocked. I told to remove "*.whatsapp.com" from their allowlist, because having "*web.whatsapp.com" on the denylist and "*.whatsapp.com" on their allowlist will result in allowing web.whatsapp.com

On Escalation Ticket # 00421750 the new comment has been added: Cristian-Alexandru Halmajan:

Hi Andrei,

I hope you are well.

As Robert mentioned in a previous comment, please ask the customer to remove "*.whatsapp.com" from their allowlist, because having "*web.whatsapp.com" on the denylist and "*.whatsapp.com" on their allowlist will result in allowing web.whatsapp.com

Ask the to do the above and they still have issues with it, we will definitely need a new set of logs. If they don't send a new set of logs dev team will not be in a position to successfully debug and further investigate the issue.

Thank you,
Cristi
